];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Are portable electric heaters expensive to run?",
    a: "It's simple maths you can do yourself. A 1500 W heater uses 1.5 kilowatt-hours per hour of use. At a typical Australian rate of roughly 30–35c per kWh, that's about <strong>45–53 cents an hour</strong>. Running one heater in the room you're using for a few hours an evening is usually far cheaper than heating the whole house — that's where the saving comes from, not from the heater itself being special.",
  },
  {
    q: "Do 'energy saving' heaters actually save money?",
    a: "Not in the way the marketing implies. All electric resistance heaters are close to 100% efficient at turning electricity into heat, so a 1500 W unit from one brand produces essentially the same warmth as any other 1500 W unit. What genuinely reduces your bill is heating a smaller area, for less time, with a thermostat and timer so it isn't running when you don't need it. Treat any claim of dramatic bill reductions with suspicion.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is it safe to leave a portable heater on overnight?",
    a: "Look for tilt protection and overheat protection — both are standard on every heater in this guide — and a thermostat so it cycles rather than running flat out. Even so, manufacturers generally advise against leaving heaters unattended for long periods. Keep it clear of curtains, bedding and furniture, never run it from an extension lead, and follow the instructions that came with it.",
  },
  {
    q: "What size heater do I need for my room?",
    a: "As a rough guide, a compact 1200–1500 W heater comfortably handles a bedroom, home office or study of roughly 15–20 m². Larger open-plan living areas need either a higher-output unit, an oscillating model to move the heat around, or simply more time. Trying to heat a big open space with a small personal heater is the most common reason people conclude a heater 'doesn't work'.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do you rate these products?",
    a: "Our Insider Score weighs verified customer ratings (50%), review volume and consistency (20%), value for money (15%), and brand reliability and buyer protection (15%). For direct-sold products with no retailer review aggregate, we say so plainly and score on verifiable specifications, certification and guarantee instead. See our full <a href='/how-we-rate/'>methodology</a>.",
  },
];
---

<ReviewPage
